WEBVTT

00:04.566 --> 00:06.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Good evening
on this Independence Day.

00:06.200 --> 00:07.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm William Brangham.

00:07.200 --> 00:09.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Judy Woodruff is off.

00:09.200 --> 00:13.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight: North
Korea claims it successfully
tested a long-range missile

00:13.433 --> 00:15.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
capable of reaching the U.S.

00:15.466 --> 00:18.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What options remain for
the Trump administration?

00:18.566 --> 00:23.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then: relocating the bushmen
-- after being forced out of
their homeland, the struggle

00:23.200 --> 00:27.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for the few remaining
hunter-gatherers in Botswana
to preserve their culture.

00:27.533 --> 00:31.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: Officially,
nobody is allowed to return.

00:31.700 --> 00:36.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the years, some have
tried to recreate life in the
villages, but they say it's just

00:37.333 --> 00:38.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not the same.

00:38.833 --> 00:40.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And what's
the buzz on a new beer?

00:40.966 --> 00:45.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
How a lab discovered a
new type of yeast from
bees that's changing the
game for beer makers.

00:47.800 --> 00:49.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB DUNN, North Carolina
State University: We actually
think, based on some work from

00:49.933 --> 00:53.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
colleagues in Italy, that it's
very likely that those first
beers and breads were relying

00:54.866 --> 00:56.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on yeasts from insects, too.

00:56.800 --> 01:00.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM:
All that and more on
tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

01:03.033 --> 01:05.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:05.700 --> 01:10.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It
was North Korea's own
version of fireworks
for the Fourth of July.

01:14.866 --> 01:19.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The communist state today fired
off a new missile that may
someday put the United States

01:19.833 --> 01:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
within range of its weapons.

01:21.800 --> 01:23.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Nick Schifrin
begins our coverage.

01:23.733 --> 01:28.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: On this July
4, North Korea declared
independence from what it called

01:29.533 --> 01:31.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
American nuclear threats.

01:31.600 --> 01:35.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
The scientists and technicians
have successfully test-fired

01:35.800 --> 01:38.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the newly developed
intercontinental
ballistic missile.

01:38.666 --> 01:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: In Pyongyang,
North Koreans celebrated what
appears to be its most advanced

01:42.700 --> 01:46.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
test in its long pursuit
of a nuclear weapon.

01:46.100 --> 01:49.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The missile flew for about 40
minutes, almost straight up,
reaching an altitude of more

01:49.966 --> 01:54.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than 1,500 miles, and came
straight down 580 miles
away in the Sea of Japan.

01:57.033 --> 01:59.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On a flatter trajectory, it's
estimated the missile could
have traveled as far as 4,000

01:59.500 --> 02:02.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
miles, past Anchorage, Alaska,
says scientist David Wright.

02:02.400 --> 02:04.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WRIGHT, Co-Director
of Global Security,
Union Of Concerned
Scientists: If they shoot

02:04.466 --> 02:07.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it essentially straight up in
the air, it goes very, very
high and comes down not very

02:07.100 --> 02:09.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
far away.

02:09.133 --> 02:12.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If they then flatten it out a
little bit, it uses all that
speed to go a much longer

02:12.233 --> 02:14.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
distance.

02:14.333 --> 02:16.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: But the test
doesn't mean North Korea can
deliver a nuclear weapon.

02:16.966 --> 02:21.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's not known whether
it's mastered required
miniaturization or
guidance and separation

02:21.066 --> 02:23.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
systems that can take
years to develop.

02:23.233 --> 02:27.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID WRIGHT: As you go to
longer and longer ranges, there
are just much higher stresses,

02:27.833 --> 02:32.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
vibrations, the acceleration,
so there are a lot of forces
on this nuclear warhead.

02:34.766 --> 02:39.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't know if they have
actually done the final steps to
have a warhead that they could

02:39.233 --> 02:42.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actually put into one of these
long-range missiles and have
it work the way it's supposed

02:42.966 --> 02:44.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to.

02:44.933 --> 02:47.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NICK SCHIFRIN: As
president-elect, Donald
Trump vowed not to
let today's event ever

02:47.433 --> 02:49.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
happen.

02:49.600 --> 02:52.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As president, he tried to push
China to pressure North Korea,
but he recently admitted that

02:52.900 --> 02:54.966 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
failed.

02:54.966 --> 02:58.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, he addressed North Korean
leader Kim Jong-un, tweeting:
"Does this guy have anything

02:58.100 --> 03:00.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
better to do with his life?

03:00.233 --> 03:04.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Perhaps China will put a heavy
move on North Korea and end
this nonsense once and for all."

03:04.600 --> 03:08.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But, today, China didn't
show willingness to
apply more pressure.

03:08.233 --> 03:11.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GENG SHUANG, Chinese Foreign
Ministry Spokesperson
(through translator):
We hope all sides can

03:11.066 --> 03:15.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
remain calm and exercise
restraint, ease the tense
situation on the peninsula.

03:15.166 --> 03:19.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: And, in Moscow,
Chinese and Russian Presidents
Xi Jinping and Vladimir

03:19.266 --> 03:24.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Putin jointly called for the
U.S. and North Korea to abandon
long-held positions in order

03:25.000 --> 03:26.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to calm the peninsula.

03:26.966 --> 03:29.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VLADIMIR PUTIN, Russian
President (through translator):
We agreed to actively promote

03:29.466 --> 03:33.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
parallel freezing of
nuclear missile activities
of North Korea and
large-scale joint military

03:34.566 --> 03:36.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
drills of the U.S.
and South Korea.

03:36.600 --> 03:41.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: North Korea has
exploited the July 4 holiday
before, in 2006 and 2009.

03:43.066 --> 03:46.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But this is their most
dramatic test, and their
momentum is increasing.

03:46.300 --> 03:50.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have now launched more
missiles in the last three years
than in the last three decades.

03:50.366 --> 03:55.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID WRIGHT: I don't see a
roadblock to them being able
to continue this process until

03:57.433 --> 04:01.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they got a missile that
really had the ability to
reach the lower 48 states.

04:02.800 --> 04:05.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think it's just a
matter of time until
they reach that point.

04:05.133 --> 04:07.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: For the "PBS
NewsHour," I'm Nick Schifrin.

04:07.666 --> 04:12.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We will look
at the implications of the North
Korean test right after the news

04:12.133 --> 04:14.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
summary.

04:14.200 --> 04:18.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the day's other news: Iraqi
soldiers in Western Mosul
advanced deeper into the last

04:18.033 --> 04:21.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
pocket still being held
by Islamic State forces.

04:21.266 --> 04:24.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Fierce fighting continued in
an area packed with civilians.

04:24.600 --> 04:29.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But in Baghdad this evening,
Prime Minister Haider al-Abadi
proclaimed a big victory over

04:29.233 --> 04:31.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ISIS, or Da'esh in Arabic.

04:31.333 --> 04:35.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HAIDER AL-ABADI, Iraqi Prime
Minister (through translator):
All the displaced must return

04:35.833 --> 04:37.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to their homes.

04:37.300 --> 04:39.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are continuing to liberate
all our land from Da'esh.

04:39.666 --> 04:43.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Iraqi people ended the
myth of Da'esh in record time,
although the world thought

04:43.633 --> 04:46.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that this wasn't possible.

04:46.100 --> 04:49.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Meanwhile,
in Syria, a Kurdish-led
militia has breached
the heart of the Islamic

04:49.733 --> 04:52.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
State's self-proclaimed
capital, Raqqa.

04:52.100 --> 04:56.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The U.S.-backed forces today
punched through the wall around
the Old City and are now pushing

04:56.933 --> 05:01.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into the most heavily fortified
portion of the ISIS stronghold.

05:01.566 --> 05:05.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
President Trump's first
face-to-face meeting
with Russian President
Vladimir Putin will

05:05.433 --> 05:07.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
happen this Friday.

05:07.366 --> 05:11.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They will meet on the sidelines
of the G20 summit as it
begins in Hamburg, Germany.

05:11.400 --> 05:15.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The White House says
there will be no specific
agenda for the meeting.

05:15.366 --> 05:19.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's word that Canada will
apologize to a Canadian citizen
for the alleged treatment

05:19.700 --> 05:22.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
he received at the
Guantanamo Naval Base.

05:22.866 --> 05:26.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's widely reported
that he will also be
paid nearly $8 million.

05:26.200 --> 05:30.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Omar Khadr was captured
in Afghanistan when
he just 15 years old.

05:30.933 --> 05:35.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He initially admitted to
killing a U.S. soldier and
spent 10 years at Guantanamo.

05:35.266 --> 05:40.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Khadr says his confession was
coerced, and Canada's Supreme
Court has now ruled he was

05:40.233 --> 05:43.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
interrogated under what it
called oppressive circumstances.

05:43.433 --> 05:47.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In New Jersey, the three-day
government shutdown is over.

05:47.966 --> 05:51.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Democratic lawmakers reached
a budget deal last night,
and Republican Governor Chris

05:51.300 --> 05:53.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Christie signed it into law.

05:53.800 --> 05:57.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Christie had been heavily
criticized for using a
state beach on Sunday,
after it was closed

05:57.966 --> 05:59.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to the public.

05:59.933 --> 06:03.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The new budget agreement allowed
state parks and beaches to
reopen for everyone just in

06:03.333 --> 06:04.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
time for the Fourth of July.

06:04.466 --> 06:06.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Pretty excited.

06:06.466 --> 06:08.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're going to see the Statue
of Liberty, so we're pretty
excited to be back here.

06:08.933 --> 06:13.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I saw on the news yesterday
that it was closed for budget
issues, so it's pretty cool.

06:13.100 --> 06:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOMAN: It's my first time.

06:14.433 --> 06:15.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Our first time.

06:15.933 --> 06:17.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: Well, it's amazing
that it opened in time.

06:17.933 --> 06:19.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's very thankful,
and it's a very special
day to reopen Liberty Park.

06:19.966 --> 06:24.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In Maine,
Governor Paul LePage also
signed a new budget, ending a

06:24.033 --> 06:26.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
partial government
shutdown in his state.

06:26.833 --> 06:31.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in Illinois, there was
no break in a budget impasse
that's now in its third year.

06:31.333 --> 06:36.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
