46:58.166 --> 47:02.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Continuing
our theme of national parks,
the Channel Islands National

47:02.666 --> 47:06.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Park -- they're off the coast
of Southern California -- was
the site of a recent discovery

47:06.800 --> 47:11.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of part of a Pygmy mammoth, a
species of ancient elephant that
roamed the Earth 13,000 years

47:12.833 --> 47:15.400 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ago.

47:15.400 --> 47:18.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This story was produced
by students from Etiwanda
High School in Southern
California, part of

47:18.166 --> 47:20.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the "NewsHour"'s
Student Reporting Labs.

47:20.200 --> 47:23.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's narrated by rising high
school senior Nick Hinojosa.

47:23.800 --> 47:28.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK HINOJOSA: Off the
California coast lies
Channel Islands National
Park, where archaeological

47:30.300 --> 47:32.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
discoveries are
still being made.

47:32.433 --> 47:36.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Laura Kirn is the chief of
cultural resources for the
Channel Islands National Park.

47:36.166 --> 47:37.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAURA KIRN, Chief of
Cultural Resources, Channel
Islands National Park:
Channel Islands national

47:37.833 --> 47:40.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
park is world-famous
for its archaeology.

47:40.800 --> 47:45.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Channel Islands really represent
a part of California that
doesn't exist on the mainland

47:46.300 --> 47:48.333 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
anymore.

47:48.333 --> 47:52.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And because we don't
have burrowing animals
here, the archaeological
record, the evidence

47:54.633 --> 47:57.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the ground is intact.

47:57.700 --> 48:00.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that is unheard of.

48:00.233 --> 48:03.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK HINOJOSA: The
preservation of the islands'
archaeology has made it
possible for new artifacts

48:03.533 --> 48:08.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be discovered, such as a
mammoth skull excavated in
fall 2016 on Santa Rosa Island.

48:10.466 --> 48:14.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Monica Bugbee, a preparator and
archaeologist for the mammoth
site in South Dakota, has

48:14.533 --> 48:18.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
begun the painstaking
process of removing the
skull from its plaster cast.

48:18.566 --> 48:22.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MONICA BUGBEE, Preparator:
This is kind of an
exciting discovery
because Pygmy mammoths,

48:22.600 --> 48:26.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
even though they're really
cool, everybody likes them
because they're small, they're

48:26.166 --> 48:28.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
neat, we actually don't
know a whole lot about them.

48:28.233 --> 48:32.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This guy was found by a
park service intern who
was doing a stream survey.

48:32.733 --> 48:37.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, they were just doing
routine walk down a canyon,
and they happened to notice it.

48:39.700 --> 48:41.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK HINOJOSA: The intern who
discovered the skull, Peter
Larramendy, was a recent college

48:41.933 --> 48:45.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
graduate who recognized the
tusk sticking out of the wall
could be something much more

48:45.666 --> 48:46.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
than just a rock.

48:46.833 --> 48:48.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LAURA KIRN: He was
part of the excavation.

48:48.833 --> 48:53.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was something that you dream
about as a child, discovering
something like a dinosaur

48:54.166 --> 48:56.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or something really exciting.

48:56.733 --> 49:00.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK HINOJOSA: Don Morris
is a retired archaeologist
for the National Park
Service who aided in

49:00.200 --> 49:02.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the excavation of
this discovery.

49:02.266 --> 49:06.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DON MORRIS, National
Park Service: I think
I can confidently say
this is the best skull,

49:07.866 --> 49:10.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Pygmy mammoth skull, that's
ever come off the island.

49:10.200 --> 49:12.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Certainly, it's the best
one I have ever seen.

49:12.933 --> 49:17.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MONICA BUGBEE: This skull
in particular, because
it looks like it might
be in the middle of

49:17.533 --> 49:22.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the two species, Columbian and
Pygmy, it can give us a much
better idea of how that process

49:23.133 --> 49:24.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
actually worked.

49:24.833 --> 49:27.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You know, how did they
actually dwarf from
Columbians to Pygmies?

49:27.900 --> 49:32.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK HINOJOSA: Scientists used
radiocarbon dating to discover
how long ago this mammoth

49:32.466 --> 49:34.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was alive.

49:34.433 --> 49:38.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This kind of dating is done
by measuring the amount of
carbon-14 in a sample and using

49:38.033 --> 49:40.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
its half-life to calculate
how old the sample is.

49:40.566 --> 49:45.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MONICA BUGBEE: There was some
charcoal that we found in the
dirt, and we radiocarbon dated

49:45.333 --> 49:50.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that, and it's about 15,000
years old, I believe, so this
guy's actually pretty young.

49:52.366 --> 49:55.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK HINOJOSA: Justin Wilkins,
a curator at the mammoth site,
has been working with Bugbee

49:55.533 --> 49:57.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
