the skull for display.

49:57.600 --> 50:02.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUSTIN WILKINS, Curator: So
in looking at the past, we can
then access how our species

50:04.000 --> 50:06.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or other species handled
changes in the environment.

50:06.300 --> 50:07.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, we look at the mammoths.

50:07.866 --> 50:09.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We look at humans.

50:09.933 --> 50:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We also look at a bunch of
small animals to see how those
animals handle these changes,

50:16.333 --> 50:19.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and then try to decide, predict,
based on the information and
patterns we see from these

50:19.466 --> 50:24.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
specimens, what patterns we're
seeing in the present, how
that's going to change in the

50:24.266 --> 50:26.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
future.

50:26.566 --> 50:28.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK HINOJOSA: Much
of archaeology still
depends on careful
observation and human work.

50:28.733 --> 50:30.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DON MORRIS: You have
got to move dirt.

50:30.800 --> 50:35.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have got to keep your
eyes open and pay attention
to what you're observing.

50:35.000 --> 50:40.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAURA KIRN: It's incredibly
exciting to think that
these things are still
out here, they're

50:41.933 --> 50:45.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
still very fragile, and we
want to protect them and
study them in the right ways.

50:45.700 --> 50:50.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it doesn't mean that people
can't still discover exciting
new things that happen to

50:52.133 --> 50:56.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be thousands of years
old on Santa Rosa Island.

